            "response_id": "resp_b6ed77d91f7e8f77006a3ebc8140548190b275d9e8f366cb3a",
            "role": "assistant",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Kubernetes (often “K8s”) grew out of Google’s long experience running large-scale containerized workloads.\n\n- **Origins at Google (pre-2014):** Google had internal cluster managers—most famously **Borg** (and later ideas from **Omega**)—that handled scheduling, scaling, and keeping services running reliably. Kubernetes was designed to bring similar patterns to the broader industry. \n\n- **Open-sourced in 2014:** Google **open-sourced Kubernetes** in **2014**, positioning it as a portable, declarative system for deploying and operating containerized applications (rather than an internal-only tool). \n\n- **Community governance via CNCF (2015):** In **2015**, Kubernetes was **donated to the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF)**, helping establish neutral, vendor-independent governance and accelerating adoption across the ecosystem. \n\n- **Maturation into a standard platform (2015 →):** Kubernetes evolved quickly from early releases into a widely adopted orchestration platform, becoming a core part of “cloud native” computing—supporting features like desired-state reconciliation, service discovery/load balancing, and extensibility through APIs and controllers. \n\nIf you want, I can also give a short timeline of major milestones (1.0, Helm, CRDs/operators, etc.) and why each mattered.",
                "annotations": [],
                "logprobs": []
              }
            ],
            "status": "completed"
          }
